items.content_text: This species is in the group referred to as 'bark moth' because of the lines, colour and resting pose.  When sitting on tree/shrub bark, it is camouflaged to protect it from predation.

items.title: Melanodes anthracitaria
items.content_text: This species is variable.  It can be dark grey or lighter grey with black lines.  It can also have light brown markings on both forewing and hindwing (see next observation). Largish moth; eight appeared at the light-trap.

items.title: Anemosa exanthes
items.content_text: Second image displays the bright yellow hind-wing.  The resting position of this species is the 'tent' position but when flying the hindwing colour is more obvious. Five came to the light despite the cold night air.

items.title: Cycloprorodes melanoxysta
items.content_text: This species comes to the light readily however only once in the past has it landed on the sheet.  Invariably it sits on the ground using the stones and leave litter as camouflage.  This image was not posed but rather an opportunistic observation which portrays the similarity of the leaf to the moth wing shape, colour and markings.

items.title: Corunastylis morrisii
items.content_text: All other plants seen had well and truly finished flowering.  This appears to be the last one in flower.  Unfortunately the plant was somewhat coated in sand.

items.title: Eriochilus cucullatus s.l.
items.content_text: Found plants at different stages of growth.  Many scattered individuals in flower, some already in ovary stage and quite a few buds just above ground level.

items.title: Corunastylis ciliata
items.content_text: All plants discovered were only 2 - 3 cm tall and few flowers on each plant.  This is most likely due to the extreme dry conditions this last summer and this autumn.

items.title: Chrysodeixis eriosoma
items.content_text: The absence of a tiny silver 's' on each forewing distinguishes it from a related species - Chrysodeixis argentifera.  Additional image shows wings spread.

items.title: Corunastylis morrisii
items.content_text: Only three plants found in this area - this is the most advanced in flower. Other two had very juvenile buds.

items.content_text: Males are about a third of the size of the female.  Only one male and about 20 females to the light-trap this evening.

items.title: Nepticulidae spp.
items.content_text: This moth is about 2mm in length and from the group known as pigmy moths.  A characteristic, besides their tiny size, are the eye-caps.  They are extremely difficult to photograph even with a good macro lens.

items.title: Edosa spp.
items.content_text: The reddish line within the brown forewing end-tips is a definite marking rather than caused by the camera angle or flash.  Both forewings are marked alike.

items.title: Noctuidae spp.
items.content_text: At present, Australian Faunal Directory has this moth listed in the category of Species Inquirenda.  However, it has been described as Mamestra dictyota by Lower in 1902.  It is in the subfamily of Noctuinae, Tribe Hadenini.

items.title: Euproctis melanosoma
items.content_text: The ID created a challenge.  Males of this species, as featured in MOV 2 shows a white tuft end to the abdomen.  This one has an orange colour tuft as well as a black upper body and stripes on the underside of the body.  May eventually be found to be a different species.  It got knocked off the sheet by a larger insect and played dead long enough to get a photo of the underside.  Two additional images included to show the features.

items.content_text: Glad to know they are breeding in our area - both an adult and juvenile bird visiting my watering spots this past week.

items.content_text: According to Moths of Victoria Part 6, this moth is easily recognised by the long rami on the antennae and the long labial palps.  It occurs in the dry sclerophyll forest and woodlands.  Spots on the wings may vary from obvious to obsolete.

items.title: Androchela milvaria
items.content_text: Androchela milvaria is very variable.  It has a large cloudy spot on each forewing - this spot is not always obvious if it is the colour form shown in this photo.  Its peak flight time is April.

items.content_text: Comment by Martin Lagerwey:  Your elytra are from Paropsis geographica which is the common one. The red saturation sometimes occurs on recently dead species.

items.title: Paropsisterna octosignata
items.content_text: Thanks to Martin Lagerwey for ID confirmation.  His comments:   Mainly Victorian beetle is nocturnal and each observation that I have made was under bark. Light trapping is a good way to encounter one. The color of the eight dots can be red or orange or yellow but otherwise they do not vary much.
